annotation.TEXT: A line from the song “Stranger in Paradise,” from the musical Kismet. It has been recorded by multiple artists, most famously by Tony Bennett.
Skeletor was the skull-topped arch-enemy on the ‘80s animated TV show He-Man and the Masters of the Universe.
Actor-singer Noel Harrison played sidekick Mark Slate in the Man From U.N.C.L.E. spinoff series The Girl From U.N.C.L.E.
Food of the Gods is a B-movie about mysterious goo that makes animals grow huge; it was loosely based on an H.G. Wells novel.
Webster was a sitcom about an ex-football player who adopts the orphaned son of an old teammate. The son, Webster Long, was played by diminutive actor Emmanuel Lewis.
Charles Moffett was a well-known jazz drummer who accompanied such musicians as Ornette Coleman and Prince Lasha.
A paraphrase of the Hoyt Axton song “Della and the Dealer.”
The use of “bad” to mean “good” in the song “Super Bad” is known as “linguistic reclamation” or “reappropriation.”
The Air Skylon is a brand of running shoe produced by Nike, which also produces another line of running shoes called the Air Max.
“Wide Track” was Pontiac’s ad slogan throughout the ‘60s; it basically meant their wheels were set a few inches farther out than other cars.
Jimmy Carl Black was part of Frank Zappa’s band, the Mothers of Invention. Of mixed Native American ancestry, he called himself “the Indian of the group.”
Gingiss Formalwear was the source for proms and wedding parties everywhere for many years, but they went bankrupt in 2003.
Edward James Olmos is a Hispanic actor known for his parts in Miami Vice and Battlestar Galactica, among many others.
The “country boy” in Chuck Berry’s famous song “Johnny B. Goode” was originally a “colored boy”; Berry changed the lyrics to appeal more to white audiences.
An ‘80s ad for deodorant Sure featured the jingle, “Raise your hand! … You feel confident, secure!”
One of the writers’ favorite phrases, this is a reference to the ‘80s cop show T.J. Hooker.
The ad jingle for Spirograph in the ‘70s was: “I don’t believe it/I just don’t believe it/The things I can do with my Spirograph.”
George Lazenby only played Bond once; he was replaced by Sean Connery for one final film and then by Roger Moore.
A paraphrased line from the film Indiana Jones and the Temple of Doom, said by the child Maharajah (Raj Singh).
1960s Space Ghost did indeed have a pet monkey, Blip.
F.I.S.T. starred Sylvester Stallone as a man working his way up through the ranks of a truckers’ union. It was written by schlockmeister Joe Eszterhas.
The sound effect used on The Six Million Dollar Man TV show to indicate that Lee Majors was running very very fast in slow motion.
Unless you include obscure choices like Barry Nelson, who played the spy in a 1954 CBS production of Casino Royale, this sadly seems to be the consensus judgment.
Although Webster wrote several children’s textbooks in addition to his famous dictionary, he never compiled a thesaurus; that was left to Peter Mark Roget.
Wilkinson Sword is a UK brand of razors and other sharp things; the company started out in the 18th century as a maker of, yes, swords.
Darkness on the Edge of Town is a 1978 album by Bruce Springsteen.
In the bad old days of the Nixon White House, there was a team known as the Plumbers (because they stopped leaks). It was the Plumbers who were caught breaking into the Watergate.
“Huzzah” is a Ren Fest reference that was first used in MST3K Episode 303, The Pod People.
The band Boston is known for only releasing an album every eight or so years.
A paraphrase of the James Brown song “Super Bad.”
World champion gymnast Kurt Thomas made the wonderfully bad movie Gymkata, in which he defeats the bad guys with the help of randomly placed gymnastics equipment.
Gheorghe Zamfir is a Romanian musician who markets himself as “Master of the Pan Flute.”
Susan Sarandon is a blond actress known for such films as The Rocky Horror Picture Show and Bull Durham.
Pippi Longstocking, known for wearing two braids that stick straight out from her head, is the heroine of a series of children’s books by Astrid Lindgren.
Did we miss a reference? Be sure to tell us in the comments!
“One Adam-12” was how the police dispatcher opened her bulletins on the TV cop show Adam-12.
In The Wizard of Oz, the palace door guard looks through a small window at Dorothy and her friends and snaps, “The Wizard says go away!”
Marlo Thomas, daughter of actor Danny Thomas, is an actress best known for starring in the sitcom That Girl.
In the ‘80s, President Reagan sent the Nicaraguan contras tons of aid to overthrow the leftist Sandinista government, continually referring to them as “freedom fighters.”
David McCallum, who plays the villainous Castile in Master Ninja II, played Illya Kurakin in the TV show The Man From U.N.C.L.E.
Johnny Storm, aka the Human Torch of the Fantastic Four, shouts “Flame on!” when he ignites.
Brought to you by the Official MST3K YouTube Channel.
Her face is based on the death mask of a young drowning victim pulled from the Seine in the late 19th century.
Three.
In the ‘60s, Baskin-Robbins offered a flavor called Dating Game, thanks to the game show’s popularity: pink ice cream with dates and butter pecans.
U-Haul launched 12 years after Ryder, renting trailers out of gas stations.
The origins of this joke are unknown, but it probably came out of late 19th-century music hall comedies, which preceded vaudeville.
Delta Burke is a curvy actress best known for her role as Suzanne Sugarbaker on the TV series Designing Women.
Scars on the forearms from intravenous drug abuse are called “tracks”—addicts hide them with long-sleeved shirts.
Bryan Ferry is a British musician who rose to fame during the ‘70s as the lead singer for Roxy Music.
The Oldsmobile Cutlass was a midsize car introduced in 1966; the “Supreme” was the high-end version.
The Garden Weasel is a home gardening product that promises to loosen the soil and uproot weeds.
Sybil Danning is the platinum blonde veteran of many a dreadful B-movie, including Chained Heat and Battle Beyond the Stars.
While clearly meant to refer to his character, in real life Lee Van Cleef was married three times and had four kids.
Red Wing Shoes is a Minnesota-based company that makes athletic shoes and work boots.
Other things that have been claimed to smell like Fritos: dog paws, human feet, dirty towels, and babies. The reason: the presence of proteus bacteria and their yeasty scent.
In the ‘80s, media mogul Ted Turner announced plans to add color to classic B&W films, which caused an uproar. He went ahead, but colorized movies never caught on.
Noah Webster was a lexicographer, writer, and editor who published his famous An American Dictionary of the English Language in 1828.
Chico Marx’s Tyrolean hat and terrible Italian accent became famous in the Marx Brothers’ series of films, including Duck Soup and Animal Crackers.
The Stan Freberg song “John and Marsha” uses only those two names to tell an entire story, in a parody of soap opera dialogue.
The Last Boy Scout is a film starring Bruce Willis and Damon Wayans as a detective and an ex-quarterback who team up to solve a murder.
A Shot in the Dark is a film starring Peter Sellers as the bumbling Inspector Jacques Clouseau, the second in the Pink Panther series.
The bearded Francis Ford Coppola is a highly respected film director and screenwriter known for such classics as The Godfather and Apocalypse Now.
A line from the film Monty Python and the Holy Grail, from a scene in which John Cleese is trying to dump his protesting elderly relative on the plague cart.
Lech Walesa is a labor organizer who helped found Poland’s first independent labor union; he later became president of Poland after its communist government collapsed.
Cosmetics maker Bonne Bell makes Lip Smackers lip gloss in the flavor of Dr Pepper, the popular soft drink.
All My Children ran on ABC for 41 years, from 1970-2011.
In the film Dog Day Afternoon, Al Pacino tries to rile up a mob to help him escape after robbing a bank by starting a chant reminding them of an infamous prison riot.
Welcome Back, Kotter was a TV series starring Gabe Kaplan as the teacher of a group of teens called the Sweathogs (one played by a young John Travolta).
The Sixfinger was a mid-‘60s finger-shaped toy gun/ballpoint pen.
Figure skater Scott Hamilton took home a gold medal from the 1984 Olympics.
Paper Moon is a film about a Bible-peddling scam artist (Ryan O’Neal) lumbered with a young child (real-life daughter Tatum O’Neal).
Then Came Bronson starred Michael Parks as a young man searching America for personal meaning. Apparently Frank Conniff adored it.
A line from the song “Ebony and Ivory” by Stevie Wonder and Paul McCartney, which preaches racial harmony by way of the piano keyboard.
George Lazenby, who plays Mallory in Master Ninja II, played James Bond in On Her Majesty’s Secret Service.
“Matchmaker, Matchmaker” is a song from the musical Fiddler on the Roof.
An imitation of the announcer on the ‘60s TV show Batman. He would close each episode by urging viewers to tune in again, “same bat time, same bat channel.”
On the TV show Rowan & Martin’s Laugh-In, Arte Johnson would pop out of some bushes to tell the audience that the previous sketch was “Very interesting, but stupid!”
“I like to watch” is a line from the movie Being There, which starred Peter Sellers as a simple gardener who becomes a celebrity.
In the Marx Brothers movie A Night at the Opera, Groucho orders dinner, including repeated requests for different numbers of hard-boiled eggs.
Tales From the Crypt was based on the ‘50s EC horror comic book by the same name.
The Heath Bar is named after its creator, L.S. Heath, who first marketed it in 1914.
A line from an ‘70s ad jingle written for the International Ladies’ Garment Workers’ Union (ILGWU).
Master Ninja II: Fully annotated by The Official MST3K YouTube Channel.
On the TV show Cheers, the entire bar would yell “Norm!” when bar regular Norm Peterson (George Wendt) entered.
A line from Minneapolis comedian Joe Keyes’ standup routine, in a bit about Jesus waterskiing without a boat.
Jim Seaborn was a hockey player with the Chicago Cardinals and other teams in the ‘20s.
Grantsburg is a tiny town in Wisconsin, population about 1,300.
The Southern-fried Tom Bodett shills for Motel 6 with the famous catchphrase, “We’ll leave the light on for you.”
Shaggy, the scruffy, goateed coward on the Scooby-Doo animated TV series, was voiced by Casey Kasem, the well-known syndicated DJ.
Two.
An imitation of Eric Von Zipper (played by Harvey Lembeck), the outlaw biker from Beach Blanket Bingo.
Markham founded a film production house in 1992 that has produced documentaries for the History Channel and for A&E Biography.
“This time, it’s personal” is the often parodied tagline of 1987’s Jaws: The Revenge.
This sounds like the beginning of the theme song to The Time Tunnel.
A paraphrased line from the movie Monty Python’s The Meaning of Life.
A line from the song “I’ll Be Seeing You,” which has been recorded by Bing Crosby, among many others.
Tahitian Treat is a fruit-punch-flavored carbonated soft drink.
Nicks also had widely known problems with cocaine and alcohol before entering rehab in 1986.
Sanders was actually born in Indiana but moved to Kentucky in his early 30s. In ads for his restaurants he had a notable Southern accent.
An imitation of Lucille Ball on I Love Lucy; “Ricky” would be Ricky Ricardo, her husband on the show (played by real-life husband Desi Arnaz).
A paraphrase of an exchange between Inigo Montoya and the Man in Black during their famous duel in the film The Princess Bride.
Of Mice and Men is a short novel by John Steinbeck about two drifters who get jobs on a ranch in California during the Depression. Things go tragically awry.
Give and go is a sports move that involves one player passing off the ball to a teammate, repositioning himself, and then getting the ball back and taking his shot.
The Garden Weasel was snapped up in 1974 by the owner of the Faultless Starch company, who suspected people were not going to be starching their shirts for much longer.
Pop singer Linda Ronstadt dated California governor Jerry Brown for a time in the ‘70s. She posed in roller skates on the album cover for Living in the USA during that time.
Graffiti Bridge is a Prince film, a sequel to Purple Rain. The bridge was located in Eden Prairie, MN, home of Best Brains. It was torn down in the early ‘90s.
The multilevel marketing company Amway has had numerous legal problems over the years, frequently accused of being a pyramid scheme.
Resusci Annie is a realistic mannequin that has been used to train people to perform CPR since 1960.
Wacky Wall Walkers were a fad during the early ‘80s. Shaped something like an octopus, they would stick to walls and slowly “walk” their way down to the floor.
The 1972 Rick Nelson song “Garden Party” is based on an incident when Nelson was booed off the stage at Madison Square Garden. It was his last Top 40 hit.
Promotions for the 1972 horror film Last House on the Left told audiences, “To avoid fainting, keep repeating to yourself, ‘It’s only a movie, it’s only a movie.’”
When Robin Hood first meets Little John, they fight with quarterstaffs to decide who has right-of-way on a bridge. Little John wins, and they end up fast friends.
“Original recipe” is the name used for the secret recipe of Kentucky Fried Chicken, invented in 1940 by Colonel Harland Sanders.
An imitation of the Crypt Keeper, the decayed host of the TV horror anthology series Tales From the Crypt.
A line from the film The Guns of Navarone.
Poor Little Rich Girl: The Barbara Hutton Story was a 1987 TV movie about the heiress to the Woolworth fortune.
A line from the song “Spinning Wheel” by Blood, Sweat & Tears.
James Bond has driven Aston Martins for 50 years in films (and in the novels as well).
An imitation of KITT, the talking car from the ‘80s TV show Knight Rider. The car’s voice was supplied by William Daniels.
Pearl Drops ads in the ‘70s & ‘80s had people passing their tongue weirdly over their teeth, reveling in their smoothness and whiteness.
At the end of the film Harold and Maude, Bud Cort (playing Harold) plays a banjo and dances along the top of a cliff.
Microsoft tech support isn’t known for being better or worse than any other company, but tech support in the industry as a whole has a pretty dismal rep.
Ossie Davis was a black actor, director, and activist who appeared in a number of Spike Lee’s films; he also directed films and wrote plays.
The Master was the actual name of the TV series when it aired in 1984.
Brian Jones was a founding member of the Rolling Stones. He drowned at the age of 27, three weeks after leaving the band.
The rental truck company Ryder was founded in 1933 as a concrete hauling company; it had one truck, a $35 Model A Ford.
“Finger-lickin’ good” is the longtime slogan for KFC. In 1972 they used a jingle, performed by Barry Manilow, that ran “Get a bucket of chicken, have a barrel of fun.”
Ferry went on to a successful solo career after Roxy Music, with songs like “Slave to Love” and “Don’t Stop the Dance.”
Kunta Kinte is a character in the Alex Haley novel Roots, a Gambian man who is brought to America as a slave. In the miniseries, he was played by LeVar Burton and John Amos.
Ed Asner is a burly actor best known for his portrayal of crusty journalist Lou Grant on The Mary Tyler Moore Show and Lou Grant.
The Blue Man Group, three mute performers in black clothes and blue face paint, started out as street performers in New York City in the late ‘80s.
Thom McAn used to have hundreds of retail stores around the country, but is now sold only in stores like Kmart and Sears.
Chicago Transit Authority was the original name of the band Chicago; their sound featured a three-man horn section as well as guitar, bass, and keyboards.
In The Second Hundred Years, Markham played both a defrosted c. 1900 gold prospector and his grandson. (It aired in color, in 1967.)
A line from the song “Walk Like an Egyptian” by the Bangles.
At Woodstock, PA announcer Chip Monck warned attendees, “The brown acid that is circulating around us is not specifically too good. It’s suggested you do stay away from that.”
Blond, curly-haired William Katt played the title role on The Greatest American Hero in the early ‘80s. Freddie Mercury and his mustache sang lead for the British rock band Queen.
A line from “Garden Party”: “I went to a garden party to reminisce with my old friends.”
The Holiday Inn hotel chain was named after the 1942 film of the same name. It was originally suggested as a joke by the hotel’s architect, but it stuck.
“Nice Work if You Can Get It” is a George Gershwin song, originally from the Fred Astaire film A Damsel in Distress.
Loverboy was an extremely popular hard rock band during the ‘80s, with hits such as “Working for the Weekend” and “Hot Girls in Love.”
In the TV special You're a Good Sport, Charlie Brown, Charlie enters a motocross race against Snoopy and the other kids.
Of the actors who have played Bond, only Sean Connery and Roger Moore have been knighted.
In a note to a friend in 1897, author Mark Twain wrote, “The report of my illness grew out of his [a cousin’s] illness; the report of my death was an exaggeration.”
Silly String has become something of a Halloween tradition, enough of a nuisance that several cities, including Hollywood, CA, have banned it.
Michael Parks, the star of Then Came Bronson, rode a Harley-Davidson Sportster motorcycle on the show.
Malcolm Forbes published Forbes magazine and was known for lavish parties; his 70th birthday party in 1989 was especially legendary, costing about $2.5 million.
A reference to the song “Crystal Blue Persuasion” by Tommy James and the Shondells.
The Crypt Keeper was a puppet voiced by John Kassir, who also played the raccoon Meeko in the Disney film Pocahontas.
In one scene in the Coen brothers film Blood Simple, John Getz buries Dan Hedaya alive in a plowed field.
Judy and Audrey Landers were blond actresses during the ‘80s; they did a bunch of guest appearances on TV shows, as well as a lingerie spread in Playboy.
It is manufactured by Dr Pepper Snapple Group.
A paraphrased line from the film Chinatown.
Rock, paper, scissors is a classic children’s game in which the kids form shapes with their hands; a similar game was played in China around the 3rd century BCE.
Paraphrase of a longtime ad slogan for Stanley Tools.
John Astin is best known for playing family patriarch Gomez Addams on The Addams Family TV show.
David Eisenhower is the grandson of President Dwight D. Eisenhower and the husband of Richard Nixon’s daughter Julie.
An imitation of millionaire Thurston Howell, played by Jim Backus, on the sitcom Gilligan’s Island.
Horror novelist Stephen King has sold more than 350 million copies of his books worldwide.
Frodo Baggins is the hobbit hero of J.R.R. Tolkien’s Lord of the Rings. Axl Rose is the long-haired lead singer for Guns N’ Roses. Divine was a drag queen who acted in several of John Waters’ films.
Shawn Phillips released a string of albums in the ‘70s, including Contribution and Faces. Actor Tim Robbins is known for films like Bull Durham and Bob Roberts.
Re-Animator is a horror flick about a med student who discovers how to bring dead tissue back to life. It was based on the H.P. Lovecraft story “Herbert West—Reanimator.”
T.J. Hooker starred William Star Trek Shatner and Heather Melrose Place Locklear.
Annie Lennox rose to fame as the singer of the Eurythmics in the ‘80s and later launched a successful solo career.
“Three on a match is bad luck” is an old military superstition widely spread after WWI by a shrewd match manufacturer who wanted people to use a lot more matches.
Stan Lee is a writer and comic book publisher who helped create the Marvel universe and turned that company into a giant media conglomerate.
Dudley Do-Right of the RCMP battled his arch-nemesis, Snidely Whiplash, first on The Bullwinkle Show and later on a show of his own.
Multiple bus tours in LA offer narrated sightseeing trips past various tourist sites in Hollywood and celebrities’ homes in Beverly Hills.
The 1965 Herschell Gordon Lewis film Color Me Blood Red had used a similar tag line: “It’s just a movie.”
An imitation of Lou Gossett Jr. as the demanding Marine Gunnery Sergeant in An Officer and a Gentleman.
The Rosetta Stone has writing on it in three languages—hieroglyphic and demotic Egyptian, and Greek—which meant scholars could finally decipher ancient hieroglyphics.
Five.
The Groovie Goolies was a short-lived 1970 animated series about a rock band of monsters; it was a spinoff of Sabrina the Teenage Witch.
Bil Keane was the creator of the comic strip “The Family Circus.”
Gideons International is an organization founded in 1899 that places Bibles in hotel rooms, hospitals, prisons, and schools.
At the end of Easy Rider, the two hippie bikers (Peter Fonda and Dennis Hopper) are shot to death by a couple of country boys in a pickup truck.
“Is it true blondes have more fun?” was a slogan for Clairol in the ‘60s.
The announcer on Batman was voiced by executive producer William Dozier.
Sky King was a radio and TV show about the adventures of plane-flying rancher Schuyler “Sky” King and his niece Penny.
Mighty Mike was a line of battery-powered toy trucks made by Remco in the ‘60s; its box boasted of its “climb-action traction.”
An imitation of Jackie Gleason in his role as Ralph Kramden on TV’s The Honeymooners.
And now, the fully-annotated Master Ninja II!
A line from the Beatles song “I Am the Walrus,” off their Magical Mystery Tour album.
Female rapper Queen Latifah has a fondness for regal headdresses, as is befitting a queen.
Ol’ Blue Eyes Is Back is a 1973 comeback album by Frank Sinatra.
Space Ghost was a cartoon superhero who fought supervillains in space during the ‘60s. In the ‘90s he hosted a talk show on the odd little show Space Ghost Coast to Coast.
Harry, the Guy with the Snake on His Face (played by John Candy) ran the adult book and video stores in Melonville on the Canadian sketch comedy show SCTV.
The Snickers candy bar was named after the Mars family’s favorite horse.
A group of rats occasionally appeared in the background of The Muppet Show; their leader was Rizzo the Rat, named after Dustin Hoffman’s character in Midnight Cowboy.
Another line from the Ricky Nelson song “Garden Party.”
In MST3K Episode 301, Cave Dwellers, Ator manages to construct a hang glider in about two minutes out of—I dunno, sticks and fresh deerskin?
The didgeridoo is an English term for the Aboriginal instrument; tribal names vary and include yirtakki, gunbarrk, and ngarrriralkpwina.
Castile soap is a term for soap based on vegetable oil, often olive oil; it is named after the Castile region of Spain.
The Bionic Boy was a TV movie starring Vincent Van Patten as an injured boy who gets various bionic parts. Vincent is Dick’s son and therefore Tim’s nephew.
An imitation of comedian Joe Besser as Oswald “Stinky” Davis, a bratty character he played on The Abbott and Costello Show.
The founder of the Audubon Society, which helps preserve birds and their habitats, was named George Bird Grinnell.
Four.
The witch’s guards and monkeys shout “Hail Dorothy!” after she disposes of the Wicked Witch of the West in The Wizard of Oz.
“The Lady Is a Tramp” is a song from the musical Babes in Arms. It was a signature song for Frank Sinatra.
In The Wizard of Oz, after Dorothy’s house crash-lands in Oz, the Wicked Witch of the West demands, “Who killed my sister? Who killed the Witch of the East? Was it you?”
Mannix was a TV series starring Mike Connors as Joe Mannix, a private eye in LA who indulged in frequent car chases, shootouts, and fistfights.
An imitation of Rod Serling as the narrator of the 1973 TV “documentary” In Search of Ancient Astronauts.
A line from the Johnny Nash song “I Can See Clearly Now.”
An imitation of comedian and Denver radio personality Michael Floorwax.
Ken Berry is a sitcom actor—he played Captain Parmenter on F Troop and Vinton Harper on Mama’s Family, among others.
An imitation of Sgt. Grover (played by Ken Lynch) on the TV series McCloud.
The Dodgers baseball team were known as the Robins until the 1930s.
Ed Roth was a custom car designer known especially for his custom hot rods in the ‘60s.
Start the Revolution Without Me is a film starring Gene Wilder and Donald Sutherland as two sets of identical twins who swap identities on the brink of the French Revolution.
Character actor Monte Markham, who plays the CIA chief in Master Ninja II, is still around and still working, with fairly recent guest shots on Leverage and Fringe.
The Great Lakes Dragaway is a racetrack near the Illinois/Wisconsin state line.
The famous theme to the James Bond films was composed by Monty Norman (although composer John Barry has claimed he actually wrote the theme).
The blustery southern Senator Beauregard Claghorn was a character on radio’s The Fred Allen Show. He was parodied in Warner Bros. shorts by Foghorn Leghorn.
When Nintendo released the Game Boy in 1989, the addictively simple game Tetris was packaged with it, after a legal battle complex enough to give you migraines.
Obi-Wan Kenobi (played by Alec Guinness) is an old Jedi Knight, a master of the mystical Force, in the 1977 sci-fi film Star Wars.
In Shake ‘N Bake ads from the ‘60s & ‘70s, a woman would tell her husband they used Shake ‘N Bake to make dinner, and her little daughter would pipe up, “And I helped!”
Beginning in the early ‘80s, Dodge trucks built by Chrysler used the ad slogan “Built Ram tough.”
A line from MST3K Episode 207, Wild Rebels.
Chicago is often referred to as the “rock and roll band with horns.”
Tony Scott directed the racing film Days of Thunder; he was known for his frenetic, fast-paced style.
With annotations provided by The Annotated MST website.
Eight Is Enough starred half-brother Dick Van Patten as family patriarch Tom Bradford. The writers’ mistake is understandable; Dick was 31 years older than Tim.
A sci-fi trope, the first universal translator appeared in the 1945 Murray Leinster novella “First Contact.”
Did we miss any references? Let us know in the comments!
Zubaz, bright shorts and pants popular in the early ‘90s, were originally marketed to weightlifters.
At the end of the terrible caper film Hudson Hawk, Bruce Willis and Andie MacDowell escape from a castle in a contraption that looks like Leonardo da Vinci’s glider.
Clothing designer Gloria Vanderbilt inherited a $5 million trust fund from her father when she was a baby, the subject of much bitter legal wrangling among her relatives.
Matt Houston was a TV series about a rich Texas oilman with a magnificent mustache (played by Lee Horsley) who solved crimes for fun.
Mr. Bubble is a brand of bubble bath. Its ad mascot is an anthropomorphized soap bubble.
Fitness expert Jim Fixx helped start America’s love affair with jogging. In 1984, he died of a heart attack while running, which many people find ironic.
“Woody” is Woody Guthrie, another folk singer best known for penning “This Land Is Your Land.”
“Spanish Flea,” performed by Herb Alpert and the Tijuana Brass, was played to introduce the bachelors on The Dating Game.
A line from Act V, Scene 1 of Hamlet, in which Hamlet is reminiscing over the skull of his former jester, often misquoted as “Alas, poor Yorick. I knew him well.”
“Dominus vobiscum” (“The Lord be with you”) is a form of devout salutation employed at the beginning of certain formal prayers in the Catholic Church.
A Big Hand for the Little Lady is a western about a high-stakes poker game starring Henry Fonda; it’s based on an earlier TV movie with Walter Matthau.
A line from the song “You’ll Never Know”; Frank Sinatra and Dick Haymes recorded popular versions of it.
A recording of the classic Abbott and Costello routine “Who’s on First?” is preserved in the Baseball Hall of Fame in Cooperstown, New York.
A series of TV ads for Excedrin pain reliever in the ‘80s had the sufferer say, “I’ve got a headache this big, and it’s got Excedrin written all over it.”
What Ever Happened to Baby Jane? is a film about a former child actress (Bette Davis) with a grudge against her wheelchair-bound sister (Joan Crawford).
Studs Terkel was a writer and broadcaster. In 1974 he published a book of oral history, Working, about people’s attitudes toward their jobs.
As mentioned earlier, that would be half-brother and nephew. Joyce Van Patten is Dick Van Patten’s sister, which would make her Tim’s half-sister.
Playwright and screenwriter Clifford Odets tended to focus on the underprivileged and their struggles against the ruling class.
The Little Drummer Girl is a novel by John le Carré about an actress who gets caught up in an Israeli spy plot.
RF, or radio frequency, cable is an older kind of cable that carries a composite video and audio signal; it has largely been replaced by S-video cable.
Uncover the truth about every reference in the film.
A line from and an imitation of gibberish-spouting frontiersman Howard Johnson in the film Blazing Saddles.
At the 1972 Olympics in Munich, a Palestinian terrorist group murdered 11 Israeli athletes and coaches. The games went on, but the surviving Israelis returned home.
Meat Loaf is a large singer/songwriter who peaked in the ‘70s with such songs as “Paradise by the Dashboard Light.”
Lauren Bacall’s famous line in To Have and Have Not: “You know how to whistle, don’t you, Steve? You just put your lips together and ... blow.”
The Loneliness of the Long Distance Runner is a film about a young man sent to a British reform school who finds solace in running.
A line from the Steely Dan song “Haitian Divorce.”
An old Alka-Seltzer ad featured a man moaning, “I can’t believe I ate the whole thing,” and being reproached by his smug wife: “You ate it, Ralph.”
“Red Lobster, for the seafood lover in you” is the longtime ad jingle for the chain of budget seafood restaurants.
Pete Seeger and his band, The Weavers, were known for protest and pro-union songs such as "Where Have All the Flowers Gone" and "If I Had a Hammer."
On the TV show The Brady Bunch, the split-level Brady house was the quintessence of late ‘60s/early ‘70s décor.
In the ‘60s, Vitalis hair tonic ran ads in which one man would ask another in disdain, “Are you still using that greasy kid stuff?”
At the time (1976), Haiti’s ruler, Papa Doc Duvalier, encouraged “divorce tourism”; people could come to Haiti for a weekend trip and a quickie divorce.
The Time Tunnel was a short-lived 1966 TV series about two young scientists who become “lost in time.” The tunnel itself looked like a receding spiral.
A take on the Irving Berlin song “There’s No Business Like Show Business” from the musical Annie Get Your Gun.
Xanadu was based on Hearst Castle, on the Central Coast of CA, although the film used photos of Oheka Castle in Long Island, NY.
On the animated TV show The Flintstones, Fred Flintstone operated the “bronto-crane” at the quarry; his boss, played by John Stephenson, was Mr. Slate.
On the original Star Trek series, Leonard Nimoy suggested the Vulcan nerve pinch as a more appropriate fighting move for the cerebral Spock than a karate chop.
